NEWARK, N.J. (AP) — A former broker and investment advisor stole more than $2.8 million from clients to pay for his gambling and buy high-end, luxury items for himself, according to federal prosecutors in New Jersey.Kenneth Welsh, 41, of River Edge, was arrested Thursday at his home and was scheduled to make his initial court appearance later in the day. He faces four counts of wire fraud and a single count of investment advisor fraud, and it wasn’t known if he’s retained an attorney.Welsh stole the money from five clients between July 2017 and March of this year while serving as an investment advisor for a large brokerage firm, prosecutors said. He’s accused of stealing at least $2.86 million by diverting money from the clients’ brokerage accounts to accounts under his control.Prosecutors have not said how the scheme was discovered.Welsh faces up to 85 years in prison if convicted on all counts.